blog.name: angelofberlin2000
blog.title: Like a Rose trampled on the ground
blog.description:
In addition to the pain and the exhaustion, he recalled how waiting on the cross between takes became tedious. To fight the boredom, he listened to music on headphones. One particular song called "Above All" (Like a Rose ...) by Michael W. Smith helped him through his most difficult moments.

"It arrived when I was confused and angry. I didn't think I could go on. The song described how Jesus was rejected and alone. That thought took me to a place — it opened an interior door that held me while on the cross," an emotional Caviezel explained. "The experience of feeling rejected and alone as all those around me laughed while drinking their hot coffees, oblivious to what was occurring. Jesus must have felt like this — forsaken, rejected, alone, and despised. It helped me pray in a very deep way — to pray without words, to pray from the heart. The discomfort, the loneliness, the split shoulder, the raw flesh all forced me into the arms of God because I had nowhere else to go for a performance I knew I was unable to create."
Jim Caviezel, Shamelessly Catholic

title: John Wick 3 -Spoiler Free Review
body:
In honor of the Year of Keanu (2019) as it has become known by future historians I went and saw John Wick 3 last night. Due to the gore and graphic nature of the violence that was above and beyond the first two films I’m glad I didn’t go see it after dinner. The violence aside it has great moments where the series gets to make fun of itself and gave a fantastic performance by classic cast members and the standout newcomers led by Hallie Barry and her menacingly adorable dogs. 

Despite the violence, the film used familiar and new settings in stunningly unique ways. While watching the film with a New Jersey native many of the scenes were of public places very familiar to any resident of the small town we call New York City. Whether they actually went to Morocco or used leftover sand dunes outside Vancouver the desert setting for some parts were also strikingly beautiful in a way the gritty and dark Wick series had not yet been. 

This film both jumps the shark at the end but makes up for it in the best story John Wick has told so far. With both his past, present, and future getting glimpsed in touching, shocking, and sometimes thought-provoking ways. Hallie Berry had perhaps the best story beat the Wickverse has brought to us. I want far more of her in Wick 4, or even franchise this out with her character getting standalone films. 

Animals served a big part of this film and it was amazing to see on screen respect given to them by the assortment of assassins who encountered them (especially the horses). There were moments where it was obvious that the horses were CGI, or displaying a discomfort that was filmed once and repeated on screen in relatively short time frames. I’m giving the benefit of the doubt that a horse wasn’t actually that disturbed and they continued filming a scene around it - but it was obvious and broke me out of the choreography in those moments. 

With a great story, even greater cast, but some unnecessary steps towards gore I’m going to give an arbitrary score of 88/100.
